  "signature": "ed25519:b9e1d3a74f2c05816d4e9b3c72a1f0e85d3b6c9f1a4e7d2b5c8f0a3e6d9b2c5f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software QA documentation must demonstrate version control, regression testing, and formal release procedures consistent with Gradation 2 requirements for a Medium model risk application.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is deployed under a validated installation qualification (IQ) protocol. Version control is maintained via Git with tagged release branches. Regression test suite covers 147 benchmark cases including beam bending, contact mechanics, and large-displacement nonlinear scenarios. Software QA plan reviewed and approved by DePuy Synthes quality engineering. Achieves Gradation 3 — exceeds required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Numerical code verification must demonstrate that the FEA solver correctly implements the governing equations through comparison with analytical solutions or established benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "Code verification performed against NAFEMS benchmark suite (LE1, LE5, NL1, NL3) and ASME V&V 10.1 test cases. Euler-Bernoulli beam bending analytical solution comparison yields <0.1% error for linear regime. Large-displacement cantilever benchmark confirms geometric nonlinearity implementation. All verification cases documented in Verification Report VR-2023-001. Required Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI values are insensitive to further mesh refinement at the selected mesh density, with a convergence criterion of <2% change in primary QoI between successive refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence study conducted across four refinement levels (coarse: 12,400 elements; medium: 31,800 elements; fine: 78,200 elements; very fine: 194,500 elements). Richardson extrapolation applied to yield force QoI. GCI index 0.31% between fine and very fine meshes, confirming convergence. Production mesh selected at fine level (78,200 elements) achieving Gradation 3. Contact region mesh sensitivity separately evaluated with 5 contact element density levels."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver convergence must be demonstrated for all load steps; residual norms must satisfy solver tolerances documented in the analysis plan.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis employs Newton-Raphson iteration with force residual tolerance 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance 1e-5. All 11 simulations converged without bisection beyond 2nd sub-step. Maximum residual at final converged state 3.2e-6. Arc-length method confirmed unnecessary given smooth load-displacement response. Solver logs archived in repository SR-2023-NCB. Achieves Gradation 2 — exceeds required Gradation 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Analysis procedures must be documented in a formal simulation plan reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary condition application and load application must be verified against the experimental protocol.",
      "rationale": "Simulation plan SP-2023-F1717-NC reviewed and approved by two independent senior analysts. Boundary conditions replicate ASTM F1717 fixture geometry: inferior rod end fixed in all DOF, superior rod end constrained in all translational DOF except axial load direction. Load application verified against test machine crosshead displacement protocol. Pre-analysis checklist completed and archived. Independent model review confirmed boundary condition fidelity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form must capture the dominant physics of the compression-bending response including geometric nonlinearity, contact between screw and rod, and material nonlinearity of Ti-6Al-4V.",
      "rationale": "Model employs large-displacement formulation (NLGEOM ON) with surface-to-surface contact pairs at screw-rod and screw-vertebral body block interfaces. Ti-6Al-4V material response modeled using bilinear isotropic hardening (E=114 GPa, σy=880 MPa, Et=1.14 GPa) consistent with ASTM F136 coupon data. UHMWPE vertebral body block modeled as elastic-plastic with Ramberg-Osgood fit to compression coupon data. Friction coefficient μ=0.2 at metallic interfaces per literature consensus. Model form validated against independent analytical estimates of initial stiffness within 3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to measured values from the actual test articles or certified material certificates; nominal CAD geometry must be confirmed against CMM measurements of test articles.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of 3 representative screws and rods from the test lot; mean dimensions used as nominal with variability captured in UQ. Material property inputs sourced from DePuy Synthes material certificates for the specific Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture test articles (Certificate MC-2022-4471). UHMWPE block properties from compression coupon testing (n=5) conducted at the same laboratory. All inputs traceable and documented in Model Input Record MIR-2023-NC-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples must be representative of the production design intent; sample size must be sufficient to characterize variability; samples from both laboratories must be from the same manufacturing lot.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from a single manufacturing lot (Lot 2022-NCB-7.5). Six constructs tested at Laboratory A (FDA-contracted), five at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes internal). CMM inspection of all screws and rods prior to assembly confirmed dimensional conformance to drawing tolerances. Sample size sufficient for characterization of inter-specimen variability at the required confidence level per ASTM E122 guidance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must replicate the intended use environment; multiple loading rates or environmental conditions should be evaluated if clinically relevant variation exists.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (25 mm/min) per ASTM F1717. Physiological loading rates and in vivo thermal conditions not replicated. Single test condition assessed — this factor is acknowledged as below required Gradation 3 and represents the one identified gap in the credibility assessment. The limitation is accepted given the quasi-static nature of the COU and the conservative nature of the single-rate protocol relative to clinical loading. Achieved Gradation 2; required Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters must be demonstrably equivalent to the experimental conditions; any differences must be quantified and their effect on QoI assessed.",
      "rationale": "Systematic equivalency mapping performed between simulation inputs and experimental measurements. Fixture geometry in FEA confirmed against CAD drawings of ASTM F1717 fixture used at both laboratories (fixture drawings obtained from both labs). Loading point and constraint locations verified within 0.2 mm. Material certificate values compared to nominal model inputs; all within 2% of certified values. Equivalency assessment documented in EAR-2023-NC-001 with no unresolved discrepancies."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics must include both percent difference and a validation metric normalized by combined uncertainty; acceptance bounds must be pre-established in the simulation plan.",
      "rationale": "Output comparison performed using two pre-established metrics: (1) percent difference <10% and (2) E/uval < 1.96 where E is the absolute model-experiment difference and uval is the combined validation uncertainty (experimental measurement uncertainty + numerical solution uncertainty). Both metrics pre-specified in Simulation Plan SP-2023-F1717-NC prior to unblinding of experimental results. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both acceptance criteria. Results documented in Validation Report VR-2023-NC-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation must be directly relevant to the clinical and regulatory decision; the link between validation QoIs and COU QoIs must be explicitly documented.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs selected: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. These QoIs directly map to the regulatory acceptance criteria in FDA guidance for spinal implant systems and are the same QoIs used in the 510(k) predicate comparison. Yield force is the primary safety-relevant QoI (onset of permanent deformation). Stiffness is a secondary functional QoI. Force at 40 mm characterizes post-yield behavior relevant to fatigue life estimation. QoI relevance documented in COU definition document COU-2023-NC-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario must be sufficiently similar to the COU scenario that the validation evidence is credible for the intended regulatory use; any extrapolation must be explicitly bounded.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the COU scenario: same implant design, same loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), same test laboratories, same manufacturing lot as planned production. No extrapolation beyond validated regime is required for the regulatory submission. The FEA model is applied within the validated load range (0 to 40 mm displacement) for the COU. Validation-to-COU relevance assessment documented in VCR-2023-NC-001 with no identified gaps requiring extrapolation."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/depuy-synthes-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending) is accepted at Medium assurance level. All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. One factor (Test conditions) achieves Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 due to single-rate testing per ASTM F1717; this gap is accepted given the quasi-static COU and the conservatism of the protocol. Quantitative validation metrics for all three QoIs satisfy pre-established acceptance bounds. The FEA modeling framework is assessed as credible for regulatory use in the 510(k) submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw system.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
